29
00:01:45,166 --> 00:01:48,267
were supposed to be here.

30
00:01:48,487 --> 00:01:51,889
They both had to cancel suddenly yesterday.

31
00:01:53,530 --> 00:01:55,971
Life comes at us hard.

32
00:01:57,572 --> 00:02:00,394
Thankfully, through friends and friends of friends,

33
00:02:01,714 --> 00:02:03,215
we have lined up a new set of panelists.

34
00:02:03,615 --> 00:02:06,877
And I would now like the panel to introduce themselves.

35
00:02:11,254 --> 00:02:15,596
I'm Brie Code. I'm the CEO and creative director of a tiny studio based in Toronto called True Love.

36
00:02:16,116 --> 00:02:22,239
Before that I was a lead programmer at Ubisoft Montreal on Child of Light and three Assassin's Creed projects.

37
00:02:22,299 --> 00:02:25,640
And before that I wrote AI for a company of heroes at Relic.

38
00:02:27,812 --> 00:02:30,053
Hi, I'm Dr. JC Lau.

39
00:02:30,273 --> 00:02:33,114
I'm currently a tech producer at Harebrained Schemes

40
00:02:33,154 --> 00:02:34,075
working on Battletech.

41
00:02:34,475 --> 00:02:36,996
Before that, I was at Bungie as a test engineer

42
00:02:37,156 --> 00:02:40,117
working on Destiny 2 and its DLCs.

43
00:02:41,157 --> 00:02:44,318
And before I entered games, I was a professor

44
00:02:44,338 --> 00:02:46,299
in the philosophy of race and gender at Virginia Tech.

45
00:02:48,228 --> 00:02:49,729
Hello, my name is Osama Darius.

46
00:02:49,909 --> 00:02:52,190
I'm a game designer at Warner Brothers Games in Montreal.

47
00:02:52,731 --> 00:02:54,632
I'm also the coordinator of the video game programs

48
00:02:54,692 --> 00:02:56,273
at Dawson College, and I'm the co-founder

49
00:02:56,293 --> 00:02:57,714
of the Montreal Independent Game Awards.

50
00:02:59,595 --> 00:03:03,097
Hi, I'm Raf Koster, and I'm a game designer

51
00:03:03,157 --> 00:03:05,158
best known for MMOs, Ultima Online,

52
00:03:05,198 --> 00:03:07,339
Star Wars Galaxies, MetaPlace,

53
00:03:07,800 --> 00:03:12,042
and I think this might be my 20th or 21st consecutive GDC.

54
00:03:14,704 --> 00:03:15,264
It's a long run.

55
00:03:17,785 --> 00:03:21,267
So the first topic I'd like to bring up is my first job in games.

56
00:03:23,368 --> 00:03:25,529
Finding a job in games can be hard,

57
00:03:25,889 --> 00:03:28,590
but I also like to talk about how do we leave a job.

58
00:03:29,090 --> 00:03:32,892
I've seen too many developers leave a trail of burned bridges behind them.

59
00:03:34,072 --> 00:03:36,713
And I would like us to talk a little bit of how to leave.

60
00:03:37,514 --> 00:03:40,195
Could the panel please talk a little bit about how you got in,

61
00:03:40,735 --> 00:03:42,456
but also how you got out.

62
00:03:43,036 --> 00:03:45,557
If you have switched jobs since then, how did you leave?

63
00:03:46,437 --> 00:03:47,098
Any advice at all?

64
00:03:50,300 --> 00:03:51,621
Reverse the order perhaps?

65
00:03:52,201 --> 00:03:52,521
Sure.

66
00:03:53,722 --> 00:03:55,623
So I got in through friends.

67
00:03:56,163 --> 00:03:57,564
And I think that's not unusual.

68
00:03:59,325 --> 00:04:02,446
A friend of mine got lucky and landed a contracting job

69
00:04:02,506 --> 00:04:03,467
doing video games.

70
00:04:03,847 --> 00:04:06,648
And from there, ended up hired full time.

71
00:04:06,989 --> 00:04:09,570
And when they needed designers on Ultima Online,

72
00:04:09,610 --> 00:04:10,410
he recommended me.

73
00:04:11,875 --> 00:04:16,977
And there I ended up just ridiculously lucky and on the right project at the right time

74
00:04:18,898 --> 00:04:21,959
I think a lot of what I'd say about that is

75
00:04:23,180 --> 00:04:29,482
That luck needs preparation, right? If if I hadn't been doing the right kind of thing beforehand

76
00:04:29,522 --> 00:04:32,203
I probably couldn't have gotten the job as

77
00:04:32,283 --> 00:04:33,624
far as leaving

78
00:04:35,184 --> 00:04:39,266
Gosh most of the times I've left have been very very stressful and unpleasant

79
00:04:42,330 --> 00:04:46,637
I once left a job over the fact that I was asked to fire a group of people that I had

80
00:04:46,697 --> 00:04:48,881
been mentoring for two years, for example.

81
00:04:50,824 --> 00:04:52,466
And I wasn't allowed to tell them that's why.

82
00:04:52,486 --> 00:04:54,690
That was not fun.

83
00:04:57,550 --> 00:05:02,715
So I actually had a completely different career path. I studied political science and I worked as a shipping agent

84
00:05:03,015 --> 00:05:09,561
And I had a love-hate relationship with the job. Meeting people was fun, the captains and the crew and doing the paperwork is boring

85
00:05:10,482 --> 00:05:13,785
So I went to another love that I had before which was graphic and web design and I just

86
00:05:14,305 --> 00:05:16,286
Completely self-taught, I became a freelancer,

87
00:05:16,306 --> 00:05:18,867
I did all the wrong things, didn't make a lot of money,

88
00:05:19,087 --> 00:05:21,428
but at least that allowed me to learn Flash,

89
00:05:22,088 --> 00:05:23,689
and Flash allowed me to make games,

90
00:05:24,209 --> 00:05:25,289
and my games were terrible,

91
00:05:25,329 --> 00:05:26,990
but they were good enough for a portfolio.

92
00:05:27,650 --> 00:05:29,391
That's how I landed my first job in the industry.

93
00:05:31,320 --> 00:05:36,726
I left that job because basically I was too nice, and I don't mean that in a good way.

94
00:05:37,647 --> 00:05:42,473
I didn't fight for my rights, I didn't fight for a salary, and I realized after years and

95
00:05:42,493 --> 00:05:47,819
years of just waiting patiently for people to acknowledge what I deserved and to give

96
00:05:47,859 --> 00:05:52,444
it to me, that people that were much more junior than me were actually making higher

97
00:05:52,484 --> 00:05:52,864
salaries.

98
00:05:53,725 --> 00:06:01,128
And when I asked to fix that, to mend that, I was given answers and excuses.

99
00:06:01,468 --> 00:06:04,190
So after six years at the same company, finally enough was enough.

100
00:06:04,630 --> 00:06:06,931
And by leaving, I almost made double what I made before.

101
00:06:07,972 --> 00:06:08,692
So it's basically that.

102
00:06:12,553 --> 00:06:16,036
The games industry is my third industry, I would say.

103
00:06:16,997 --> 00:06:19,979
So I'm Australian, and in Australia,

104
00:06:19,999 --> 00:06:21,761
you can do a law degree as an undergrad.

105
00:06:21,901 --> 00:06:28,265
So I actually started my college with an arts law degree,

106
00:06:28,486 --> 00:06:30,427
and I went on to become a lawyer.

107
00:06:30,627 --> 00:06:32,229
I worked in family law for several years,

108
00:06:32,369 --> 00:06:33,530
working on child representation.

109
00:06:34,511 --> 00:06:36,912
in divorce cases, which is, as you can imagine,

110
00:06:36,952 --> 00:06:39,953
not a super fun place to be when you're 22 years old.

111
00:06:41,474 --> 00:06:42,274
Yeah, and then after that,

112
00:06:42,614 --> 00:06:44,295
I decided I wanted to be an academic.

113
00:06:44,355 --> 00:06:46,996
So then I did a dissertation

114
00:06:47,476 --> 00:06:48,997
in moral and political philosophy.

115
00:06:49,077 --> 00:06:52,758
So I ended up with a PhD in philosophy,

116
00:06:52,838 --> 00:06:53,619
and what do you do with that?

117
00:06:53,719 --> 00:06:56,860
You become a philosophy professor,

118
00:06:57,300 --> 00:06:59,401
because either that or there's that joke

119
00:06:59,421 --> 00:07:01,662
about going to McDonald's and asking people

120
00:07:01,742 --> 00:07:03,343
if they think they want fries with something.

121
00:07:04,823 --> 00:07:11,826
So, when I was an academic, I was like, well, I have these skills, but I want to make games.

122
00:07:12,186 --> 00:07:16,947
How do I leverage my background into a games job?

123
00:07:17,447 --> 00:07:23,970
And so I actually applied at Bungie as a tester, and I'm like, I have a PhD, I would like to

124
00:07:24,010 --> 00:07:24,630
be a tester.

125
00:07:25,770 --> 00:07:32,653
And so that was a really interesting conversation, but I guess they gave me the job, so that's

126
00:07:32,693 --> 00:07:32,873
cool.

127
00:07:34,511 --> 00:07:37,074
And so a lot of it was talking about how those skills transferred.

128
00:07:37,114 --> 00:07:40,197
So I talked a lot about like how I have particular communication skills and

129
00:07:40,257 --> 00:07:43,440
organizational skills and how I could apply them to a particular role.

130
00:07:44,541 --> 00:07:50,948
And I can't say I've left a lot of game shows because I'm the baby on this panel.

131
00:07:51,008 --> 00:07:52,870
I've been in the industry for about four years.

132
00:07:53,170 --> 00:07:55,673
But although statistically, I'm one year away from.

133
00:07:57,060 --> 00:07:59,802
the average career length for a woman in games,

134
00:07:59,862 --> 00:08:01,183
so let that sink in.

135
00:08:02,724 --> 00:08:05,166
But yeah, so one of the reasons I did leave

136
00:08:05,246 --> 00:08:09,649
was it was a combination of studio culture

137
00:08:09,769 --> 00:08:11,350
and also wanting to make an impact.

138
00:08:11,730 --> 00:08:14,612
And depending on your studio size and its composition,

139
00:08:14,632 --> 00:08:16,353
it can feel hard to make an impact.

140
00:08:17,374 --> 00:08:20,756
And so I wanted to go somewhere where I could

141
00:08:21,577 --> 00:08:23,658
feel like I was making a difference and being effective

142
00:08:23,958 --> 00:08:26,060
and seeing change that I wanted.

143
00:08:26,080 --> 00:08:26,120
So.

144
00:08:27,365 --> 00:08:28,966
Yeah, that's pretty much my story.

145
00:08:31,749 --> 00:08:33,791
I got into the games industry by accident.

146
00:08:33,811 --> 00:08:35,573
I wanna go all the way back to high school.

147
00:08:37,014 --> 00:08:39,837
I grew up in the country and I hated living in the country.

148
00:08:40,498 --> 00:08:44,361
And I figured out by looking at what's possible

149
00:08:44,401 --> 00:08:46,784
in my high school that I could finish high school

150
00:08:46,804 --> 00:08:49,967
in four years instead of five if I moved some classes around

151
00:08:50,027 --> 00:08:51,849
in a way that my teachers didn't approve of.

152
00:08:52,769 --> 00:08:53,990
and took summer school,

153
00:08:54,810 --> 00:08:56,650
and the courses that's supposed to be remedial,

154
00:08:56,690 --> 00:08:58,911
but just take it, and they couldn't stop me.

155
00:08:59,631 --> 00:09:01,852
And so I finished high school when I was 16

156
00:09:02,172 --> 00:09:04,213
and went to university with absolutely no savings

157
00:09:04,233 --> 00:09:05,433
because I never had a summer job

158
00:09:05,973 --> 00:09:07,113
and hadn't thought that far ahead.

159
00:09:08,434 --> 00:09:09,974
So I had to put myself through university

160
00:09:10,074 --> 00:09:12,155
by working two jobs and keeping my scholarship.

161
00:09:12,935 --> 00:09:15,956
And again, I kind of like figured out how to make it work.

162
00:09:15,996 --> 00:09:17,737
And I thought if I do computer science,

163
00:09:18,197 --> 00:09:18,937
I can get a degree.

164
00:09:20,458 --> 00:09:23,001
and know I can keep my scholarship because it's not subjective.

165
00:09:23,041 --> 00:09:26,985
Like you just stay in the lab until your program works and you know you have an A

166
00:09:27,005 --> 00:09:29,487
and then you know you have your scholarship and you know you have a degree.

167
00:09:29,507 --> 00:09:35,093
I graduated when I was 20 and the dot-com crash just happened and there were no jobs.

168
00:09:35,644 --> 00:09:39,425
and I realized I didn't want to be a programmer and I hadn't thought that far ahead either.

169
00:09:42,306 --> 00:09:49,388
I kept my student job for a while and then I got a credit card and I went to Europe.

170
00:09:49,868 --> 00:09:54,309
I thought that moving from the country to Vancouver had been so expansive and interesting

171
00:09:54,749 --> 00:09:56,929
that going to another continent would be interesting too.

172
00:09:58,530 --> 00:10:04,636
And I thought I would figure out what I wanted from life and what should I go back to school

173
00:10:04,656 --> 00:10:06,998
and study because I felt like I wanted to do a do-over.

174
00:10:07,719 --> 00:10:13,524
And then what I discovered was that I ran out of money and went back to Vancouver with

175
00:10:13,584 --> 00:10:17,948
eight dollars left and needed a job and started applying for every programming job I could

176
00:10:17,988 --> 00:10:23,293
find and I was very, very, very, very, very, very, very lucky.

177
00:10:23,834 --> 00:10:26,097
to get a job at Relic Entertainment in Vancouver,

178
00:10:26,137 --> 00:10:29,341
which was an amazing experience.

179
00:10:30,042 --> 00:10:31,423
I loved it from the first few weeks,

180
00:10:31,483 --> 00:10:33,846
and I knew that I would stay in the games industry forever.

181
00:10:35,789 --> 00:10:37,932
So I wrote AI Code there.

182
00:10:38,032 --> 00:10:39,433
I worked there for a while, but then I was like.

183
00:10:40,595 --> 00:10:45,120
I did want to try to live overseas for a while, so I went to Australia for a bit.

184
00:10:45,220 --> 00:10:46,301
I came back to Canada

185
00:10:48,524 --> 00:10:50,226
and then I started my own studio.

186
00:10:50,546 --> 00:10:55,492
And a couple of the times that I left studios, not all of them,

187
00:10:55,973 --> 00:10:57,795
one of those jobs was really amazing.

188
00:10:57,815 --> 00:10:58,796
All those jobs were amazing.

189
00:11:00,744 --> 00:11:05,888
Being a woman in a workplace dominated by men is not easy.

190
00:11:05,908 --> 00:11:10,191
And research shows if there's less than 30%, I think, of women,

191
00:11:10,311 --> 00:11:15,275
then women get sidelined and stereotyped and talked over in meetings

192
00:11:15,375 --> 00:11:18,037
and men attribute the women's ideas to themselves.

193
00:11:18,138 --> 00:11:20,059
And these kind of things really happen.

194
00:11:21,140 --> 00:11:27,166
eventually you kind of reach a point where you are just not able to develop

195
00:11:27,226 --> 00:11:31,911
your talents and your aptitudes at the speed that the men around you are and it

196
00:11:32,071 --> 00:11:35,995
makes more sense to go somewhere new. So that's why I left a couple of mine.

197
00:11:39,473 --> 00:11:41,714
I'm coming at you from extreme privilege.

198
00:11:42,935 --> 00:11:46,677
As a programmer, I've never been afraid to leave the game

199
00:11:46,717 --> 00:11:52,281
industry, which is a blessing for that not many others

200
00:11:52,361 --> 00:11:54,602
and specialists in the gaming field have.

201
00:11:55,803 --> 00:11:58,905
My first job in games was my first real job,

202
00:11:59,005 --> 00:12:00,886
if you did not count summer jobs.

203
00:12:01,926 --> 00:12:06,569
And it was as a programmer for games to be broadcast on TV.

204
00:12:07,842 --> 00:12:13,586
I failed my college, I did not know C++, and I lied to get in.

205
00:12:16,588 --> 00:12:21,671
I was asked to start in three weeks, and that's when I got my first book on C++.

206
00:12:27,736 --> 00:12:28,176
It worked out.

207
00:12:28,636 --> 00:12:29,117
It worked out.

208
00:12:32,379 --> 00:12:33,039
It was a different time.

209
00:12:34,218 --> 00:12:39,220
So if we talk about this first topic, and then if we try to

210
00:12:39,560 --> 00:12:44,902
think of one time where we realized that this is so bad

211
00:12:45,902 --> 00:12:50,903
or so good, an opportunity on the outside.

212
00:12:50,943 --> 00:12:53,084
Sorry for making that sentence a complete mess.

213
00:12:54,264 --> 00:12:57,385
Have we ever had such a good situation and good offer from

214
00:12:57,405 --> 00:12:58,566
the outside that you need to leave?

215
00:12:58,846 --> 00:13:01,847
Or was there ever a situation so bad?

216
00:13:03,048 --> 00:13:04,189
that you felt you had to leave.

217
00:13:05,189 --> 00:13:08,250
And I can, when my boss was screaming at me

218
00:13:08,390 --> 00:13:09,570
that she would kill me,

219
00:13:12,091 --> 00:13:13,992
that's when I left my first job.

220
00:13:15,492 --> 00:13:19,393
So, who would wanna go first on that?

221
00:13:21,814 --> 00:13:25,335
So, let's see, my first job in games that I left,

222
00:13:26,855 --> 00:13:28,876
that would have been when I left Origin

223
00:13:29,596 --> 00:13:30,897
after making Ultima Online.

224
00:13:33,315 --> 00:13:36,217
I'd come on board on Ultima Online when I was 23, 24.

225
00:13:41,321 --> 00:13:43,662
And after only a couple of years,

226
00:13:43,722 --> 00:13:45,384
I was actually the lead designer of it

227
00:13:45,604 --> 00:13:48,886
by the time I was 25 when it shipped.

228
00:13:49,427 --> 00:13:52,589
And I knew nothing about the wider industry at all.

229
00:13:52,889 --> 00:13:55,131
I didn't know anybody.

230
00:13:55,151 --> 00:13:57,052
I just didn't know anyone.

231
00:13:57,072 --> 00:14:00,135
I didn't know what I had actually accomplished.

232
00:14:00,767 --> 00:14:01,929
like I was oblivious to it.

233
00:14:02,930 --> 00:14:07,294
And I was highly opinionated,

234
00:14:08,816 --> 00:14:10,057
highly, highly opinionated,

235
00:14:10,097 --> 00:14:12,520
very sure of myself in terms of what we were doing.

236
00:14:13,121 --> 00:14:18,006
But that meant that despite having just shipped this game

237
00:14:18,066 --> 00:14:20,829
that was a really big deal,

238
00:14:23,827 --> 00:14:27,708
Some of you are young enough to not even know how big a deal it was at the time.

239
00:14:28,009 --> 00:14:30,810
It was a really big deal, but I didn't realize how big a deal it was.

240
00:14:33,071 --> 00:14:35,532
EA actually put me on the list of people to be laid off

241
00:14:36,733 --> 00:14:39,974
because I was opinionated and thought that they were idiots

242
00:14:40,534 --> 00:14:42,295
in terms of what they were doing with online games.

243
00:14:43,756 --> 00:14:46,277
I got rescued by managers who...

244
00:14:47,778 --> 00:14:50,899
I owe an enormous debt to people like Gordon Walton and Rich Vogel

245
00:14:50,939 --> 00:14:52,380
who mentored me through this period.

